A DESERT DEAL FOR BRITISH PETROLEUM

By:
EDITED BY THANE PETERSON

DESPITE A BLOODY INSURgency by Islamic militants in Algeria, British
Petroleum on Dec. 23 signed a five-year deal with Sonatrach, Algeria's
state-owned oil company, to explore and develop gas fields in the remote
I-n-Salah region of the Sahara desert. BP will foot 65% of the $3.5 billion
cost of the project and will get one-third of the gas's sales
value--enough, it figures, to boost its worldwide gas production by up to
30%. A spokesman says BP is hoping that energy installations, which account
for 95% of Algeria's foreign earnings, won't be targeted by the insurgents.
Exxon and Atlantic Richfield also are mulling deals in Algeria.

